<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-210-944  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 210 944.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Engineering  April 1989 v8 n4 pS2(10).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Integrated manufacturing: the shape of work to come. (SpecialReport: Integrated Manufacturing VII) (includes related articleson how Ford copes with technological change, and investing in thefuture.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Beckert, Beverly A.; Knill, Bernie; Pascarella, Perry; Weimer,George.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Spectacular changes are taking place in US manufacturing as aresult of major technological advancements.andP;  Many of today's jobsdid not exist in the early 1980s, while many others will cease toexist during the 1990s.andP;  Much manufacturing management today isexperimental because of the newness of the workplace.andP;  One cleartrend is the emergence of manufacturing engineering as a careerchoice.andP;  Other trends include the increased use of just-in-timeconcepts in manufacturing and distribution, and the emergence ofEDI.andP;  The success of US manufacturers depends on an educatedworkforce.andP;  Private and public organizations will have to workhard to ensure that workers are educated.andP;  The areas ofmanufacturing that are receiving the most attention are humanintegrated manufacturing, computer-integrated manufacturing andteams and partnerships.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer-Integrated ManufacturingCAD-CAMEngineeringManufacturingIndustry AnalysisTraining of EmployeesJust In Time Inventory SystemsAutomationFactory ManagementTeam ApproachHuman Factors.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>